@article{Sundberg94,
    author = {Sundberg, J.},
    citeulike-article-id = {4522308},
    comment = {A number of threads supporting the hypothesis of a universal 'frequency code':

== Universal tendencies for fundamental frequency (f0) and sentence type ==

Tendency to use high and/or rising F0 to mark questions, especially yes/no questions, and low and/or falling F0 to mark statements.  There are exceptions but the correlation is strong.  Attempts to explain via physiology have not been successful.

== The affective use of F0 ==

Anecdotal and experimental evidence in general agreement that there are cross-culturally similar uses of F0 to signal affect, intention or emotion.

Evidence has methodological problems and so is not extensive but it seems safe to conclude that such 'social' messages as deference, politeness, submission, lack of confidence are signaled by high and/or rising f0 whereas assertiveness, authority, aggression, confidence, threat are conveyed by low and/or falling f0.

Experimental results suggest that sometimes higher F0 can be perceived as having greater confidence, because this leads to a steeper 'terminal fall' in f0.

== Tone in sound symbolism ==

High tone tends to be associated with words denoting or connoting SMALL (and related concepts e.g. DIMINUTIVE, FAMILIAR, NEAR or NARROW), whereas low tone is associated with the notion LARGE, etc.

== F0 in nonhuman vocalizations ==

Cross-species similarity in form-function relationship of the acoustic component of 'close-contact agonistic displays\# (ie face-to-face competitive encounters).  Confident aggressor sounds are rough and have a low F0, submissive / non-threatening cries are tone-like with high F0, e.g. the dog's threatening growl and submissive whine/yelp.  Explained by morton (1977) by noting F0 s.is lower in bigger animals, and bigger membranes are more likely to have secondary vibrations giving rise to irregular / rough voice quality.  I.e., sound conveys an impression of size of signaler.

Perhaps high/rising tone of the questioner is from the same root, signalling subordination in someone who needs help.  In contrast, the person making a statement is self-sufficient.

== Facial expression ==

Suggests the origin of the smile is also as a signal of size, resonant affects suggesting a smaller vocaliser, and the o-face doing the opposite.

== Consonants and vowels in sound symbolism ==

Words denoting/connoting SMALL or SMALLNESS exhibit disproportionate incidence of vowels and/or consonants characterised by high acoustic frequency, and vice versa.  

== Sexual dimorphism of the vocal anatomy ==

The adult male larynx is approximately 50\% larger than the adult female's in the anterior-posterior dimension, but less in the lateral dimension.  That is, in precisely the way that gives the male longer vocal cords and thus lower F0.  The larynx is also longer, giving 15 - 20\% longer vocal tract, giving lower resonances.  Suggests this is to enhance aggressive displays -- strong evidence for an innate frequency code.},
