@article{Melara92,
    abstract = {{This research investigates the nature of similarity relations-among three pairs of interacting
dimensions: (1) the integral dimensions of auditory pitch and loudness, (2) the configural dimen-
sions of paired parentheses, and (3) the cross-modally corresponding dimensions of visual posi-
tion and auditory pitch. We evaluated the rules by which information from each di-mens-ion cornâ€”
bines in similarity judgments. Our claim is that, when judging similarity, processes that are
obligatory, or what we call mandatory processes, can commingle with processes of choice, or what
we call optional processes. By varying instructions, we found strong evidence of optional process-
ing. Instructions to rate overall similarity encouraged subjects to attend to stimuli as wholes
and led to a Euclidean rule in similarity scaling. Instructionsto focus on-dimensions encouraged
subjects to consider each stimulus dimension separately and-led-to-a-city-block rule. We argue
that optional processes may obscure mandatory ones, and so need to be identified-before-manda-
tory processes can be understood.}},
    author = {Melara, Robert D. and Marks, Lawrence E. and Lesko, Kathryn E.},
    citeulike-article-id = {4486469},
    comment = {Optional processes in similarity judgments

Separable dimensions (e.g. colour saturation and brightness) give
similarity measure with cityblock distance, and interactive dimensions
give euclidean distance (e.g. circle diameter orientation and size)
and so are (arguably) compared as perceptual whole.

However similarity judgements, including stroop interference can be
based on optional processes, not mandatory ones, with subjects highly
sensitive to the given instructions.

Integral dimensions - yield performance gain in speeded classification
whenever and however dimensions are correlated.  This crosstalk is
thought to be restricted to a sensory/perception level of processing.

Configural dimensions - geometric dimensions (e.g. height and width)
whose interaction can create a third, emergent dimension.

Corresponding dimensions - those whose pairing entails a
correspondence, e.g. cross-modal auditory pitch and visual vertical
position that move together.

Introduces results of three MDS studies, one for each category
(corresponding pitch/position, integral pitch/loudness, configural
left/right parenthesis pairs).  In all three cases subjects instructed
to make judgements based on wholes did so according to euclidean
distance, and those based on focussing on dimensions did so according
to city block distance.

"for all known forms of dimensional interaction, the structure of the
similarity space is determined largely by where subjects focus their
attention."

Optional processes undermine claims about the nature of underlying
cognitive representations, and make it difficult to identify
fundamental properties of processing.

"... mandatory processes can only be uncovered by first identifyingand
isolating the optional processes that contextualize them."
},
