@article{Medin93,
    author = {Medin, D. L. and Goldstone, R. L. and Gentner, D.},
    citeulike-article-id = {4472168},
    comment = {
Nelson Goodman's (1972) argument against similarity - it's meaningless
without a frame of reference. Similarity of A to B is an ill-defined,
meaningless notion unless one can say "in what respects" A is similar
to B.

This paper argues similarity is indeed quite flexible, but to counter
Goodman's argument is "fixed by the similarity comparison process" and
that ongoing research provides respects for similarity.

Three types of similarity:
1/ Similarity measured indirectly - e.g. using confusion errors to reveal underlying similarity (the more similar, the more likely confusion is likely (e.g. smith 1980 http://is.gd/xuvv, new/old memory tests (Gillund \& Shiffrin 1984), similar/different tests (more similar the stimuli, the longer the response time and more likely stimuli will be incorrectly judged to be the same).
2/ Direct judgements of similarity - e.g. my MDS pilot
3/ Similarity as a theoretical construct - models of cognition, which assume that similarity is either directly or indirectly computed.

Reviews criticism for similarity, including of MDS studies,
e.g. Melara, Marks and Lesko (1992) found euclidean vs city block
distance varied according to test subject instructions.

Through experiment finds similarity is "disturbingly flexible", where
respects (dimensions) are fixed by the nature of the comparison
process.

Functions of similarity:

1/ heuristic - allowing educated guesses in the face of limited
knowledge, for example guessing the danger of an unknown snake.
2/ comparison - explicit similarity comparisons and similes.  Can be
assymmetrical.

Property activation and comparison - There may be many ways in which
e.g. two countries can be compared, and it's not feasable that all are
activated in a comparison.  Comparison therefore involves a search for
properties (well, domains) to compare.

Alignment and structure - "... bringing aspects of the entities into
correspondaence" "roughly the same as the process of structural
alignment in analogical mapping".  Result depends on the context of
the particular comparison.

Reviews context effects.

Takes these views:

Similarity is not hard-wired - performance may vary with processing
time and previous experience, perceptual and conceptual similarity are
related, perceptual similarity is only shown to be stable in
particular circumstances and can be shown to be dynamic and context
dependent..

Similarity can vary with experience and context, are highly variable
but bound to the details of the comparison process.


"Nelson Goodman (1972) called similarity a chameleon, but we believe
that similarity is more like two yoked chameleons: The entities
entering into a comparison jointly constrain one another and jointly
determine the outcome of a similarity comparison. (That is,
paradoxically, two chameleons may behave in a more orderly manner than
one.)  Thus, similarity is changeable and context dependent but
systematically fixed in context.  This systematicity allows a person
to understand what other people mean when they say "X is similar to
Y," even when they do not explicitly mention respects.  Our studies
show that people's judgments of similarity reflect constraints that
serve to fix respects.  In short, although the comparison process is
dynamic, it is also lawful."

Implication for similarity theories

1/ Similarity comparisons involve mutually constraining property
instantiation and interpretations.

