Three factors in differing effects:

* Partial/complete blocking
* Difficulty of task
* Number of evaluations required

= Research questions =

== Differing effects on (a) fatigue, (b) boredom (c) stimulus knowledge (d) task insight

From review: Humphreys (1982) did not find significant differences in test-retest reliability between above methods.

Results: Fatigue and boredom lowest for sorting, somewhat higher for paired comparisons, markedly higher for conditional rankings and triadic combinations.  Stimulus knowledge and task insight constant across methods, so little evidence for learning effects in MDS judgment tasks.

== Differing effects on (a) completion time (b) occurrence of missing values ==

From review: Configurations are highly similar in general.

Results: Sorting fastest (mean of 3.2 min), followed by paired comparisons (7.8 min with) conditional ranking and triadic combinations (incomplete design using 80 out of 220 triads) taking 19.3 and 18.7 min respectively.  Paired comparisons has highest percentage who completed whole task (83.7\%), conditional ranking and sorting is slighly lower.  Triadic combinations have lowest of only 60\% completing all judgments.

== Differences with respect to (a) the recovered dimensionality (b) the amount of error (c) the recovered coordinates ==

From review: Knowledge rather incomplete and fragmented.

Results: 2D solution found for sorting and paired comparisons and 3D for conditional rankings and triadic combinations.  Error variance substantially lower for sorting (and to a lesser extent paired comparisons) than for conditional rankings and triadic combinations, indicating sorting data (and to lesser extent paired comparisons) are represented best by distances obtained with MAXSCAL. Note: doesn't seem surprising considering lower dimensionality of solution...

The perceptual map derived with MAXSCAL from paired comparison data represents the 'common underlying perceptual map' best.

Apparently, conditional ranking and triadic combinations extracts more information from the subjects. 

Dimensions 2 and 3 are both interpreted as representing country-of-origin, dimension 2 being japanese/south-european and dimension 3 separating german automobiles from other brands...

= Conclusion =

Trade off between amount of information (triadic combinations and conditional ranking) and lack of fatigue/boredom/high completion time (sorting and paired comparisons).

Sorting is fast, causing less fatigue but yields little informations for individual subjects, so no individual perceptual maps.},
