    citeulike-article-id = {3521442},
    citeulike-linkout-0 = {http://dx.doi.org/10.1007/11880172\_2},
    citeulike-linkout-1 = {http://www.springerlink.com/content/p554k50hv51665hg},
    comment = {
"... syntax is required only for the subtlest aspects of communication
-- pragmatic and semantic features are more fundamental"

"seeing language as a cause of human thinking is like seeing money as
a cause of human economics"

== Cooperation for future goals ==

Animals communicate without language.  However symbolic language of
humans allows communication about future goals (anticipatory
planning), which animals can't communicate.

== The need for symbols in communication about future goals ==

Symbolic language allows humans to make their inner worlds known to
one another, and cooperate about future goals.

"... semantics can be seen as conventionalised pragmatics."

== Semantics as a meeting of minds ==

Discusses image schemata.

"The fundamental role of communication is to affect the states of mind
of others.  A meeting of minds means that the representations in the
minds of the communicators will become suffiently compatible so that
successful joint action can arise."

== Meeting of minds as fixpoints in communication games ==

A fixpoint where through conversation both individuals reach a point
where they feel there is a mutual understanding.

"we shift from the contentional emphasis on the way we share the same
concepts to an emphasis on the way the "shape" of our conceptual
structures makes it possible for us to find a point of convergence."

"just like wheels are round because they make transportation
efficient, we expect to identify the shapes of concepts that are
selected to make communication smooth."

Description of conceptual space - euclidean psychological similarity
space.  Accords with prototype theory of concepts.

"whenever the facility to reach a meeting of minds matters, convex
mental representations provide a background over which language can
deploy most of its power."

Convexity might not provide an accurate picture of the world, but does
provide a communicable one.

"Consensus needs not to correspond to "reality": In many cases it is a
form of groupthink, convegence to beliefs dominated more by peer
pressure than truth."

},
