@article{Barsalou09,
    abstract = {{
                Based on accumulating evidence, simulation appears to be a basic computational mechanism in the brain that supports a broad spectrum of processes from perception to social cognition. Further evidence suggests that simulation is typically situated, with the situated character of experience in the environment being reflected in the situated character of the representations that underlie simulation. A basic architecture is sketched of how the brain implements situated simulation. Within this framework, simulators implement the concepts that underlie knowledge, and situated conceptualizations capture patterns of multi-modal simulation associated with frequently experienced situations. A pattern completion inference mechanism uses current perception to activate situated conceptualizations that produce predictions via simulations on relevant modalities. Empirical findings from perception, action, working memory, conceptual processing, language and social cognition illustrate how this framework produces the extensive prediction that characterizes natural intelligence.
            }},
    author = {Barsalou, Lawrence W.},
    citeulike-article-id = {4239506},
    citeulike-linkout-0 = {http://dx.doi.org/10.1098/rstb.2008.0319},
    citeulike-linkout-1 = {http://rstb.royalsocietypublishing.org/content/364/1521/1281.full.abstract},
    citeulike-linkout-2 = {http://rstb.royalsocietypublishing.org/content/364/1521/1281.full.full.pdf},
    citeulike-linkout-3 = {http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2666716/},
    citeulike-linkout-4 = {http://view.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19528009},
    citeulike-linkout-5 = {http://www.hubmed.org/display.cgi?uids=19528009},
    comment = {Survey of accumulated evidence supporting the author's theory of situated concepts -- being represented by simulations of aspects of perceptions.  Does not mention anything against the theory.

Simulation as "re-enactment of perceptual, motor and introspective states acquired during experience with the world, body and mind".

Seems to avoid talking about 'imagery' in this paper, apart from making the distinction between conscious and unconscious simulations.

Does not mention particular type of neurons such as mirror neurons.

States of perception, action and introspection are stored in long term memory, and then re-enacted as representation of concepts, useful when making predictions.

Simulators aggregate cross-modal information from across a category's instances.  They conceptualise the category by activating certain aspects of it as a simulation.  Which aspects get activated during a particular simulation depends on such things as recently, frequency and context.

Simulations are never exact reenactments of previously experienced category instances, but are partial, distorted and sometimes vague.

Purposes of simulations include: representing instances in their absence, inference and prediction production via pattern completion, conceptual combination, propositions in complex structures, representation of abstract concepts.   

Classic symbolic systems emerge implicitly from modal and association systems (rather than explicitly in the symbolic structures of calculus and frames).

Simulators develop whenever attention focuses repeatedly on a type of object (bicycle), action (pedaling), introspection (happiness) or relation (meshing of chain) in experience.

Concepts are not represented in isolation but in situations, after all perceptions always occur in situations.

A situated conceptualisation typically simulates (1) perceptions of relevant people/objects (2) actions (3) introspections) (4) settings.



[How does this relate to confabulation theory?  Confabulation seems to be just about symbols]
},
