@article{Hickok09,
    abstract = {{The discovery of mirror neurons in macaque frontal cortex has sparked a resurgence of interest in motor/embodied theories of cognition. This critical review examines the evidence in support of one of these theories, namely, that mirror neurons provide the basis of action understanding. It is argued that there is no evidence from monkey data that directly tests this theory, and evidence from humans makes a strong case against the position. The discovery of mirror neurons in macaque frontal cortex has sparked a resurgence of interest in motor/embodied theories of cognition. This critical review examines the evidence in support of one of these theories, namely, that mirror neurons provide the basis of action understanding. It is argued that there is no evidence from monkey data that directly tests this theory, and evidence from humans makes a strong case against the position.}},
    author = {Hickok, Gregory},
    citeulike-article-id = {4133323},
    citeulike-linkout-0 = {http://dx.doi.org/10.1162/jocn.2009.21189},
    citeulike-linkout-1 = {http://www.mitpressjournals.org/doi/abs/10.1162/jocn.2009.21189},
    citeulike-linkout-2 = {http://view.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19199415},
    citeulike-linkout-3 = {http://www.hubmed.org/display.cgi?uids=19199415},
    comment = {A critical yet sympathetic review of the mirror neuron theory of action understanding.

The data: Mirror neurons first discovered in frontal area F5 of the macaque monkey.  The cells activated when the monkey observed goal directed actions (hand and/or mouth movements directed towards objects), but not to visually presented objects, faces, non-goal-directed body movenemtns, goal-directed actions made using tools, mimicking of grasping an absent object, or movement preparation activity.  Further, no M1 cells (hand area of primary motor cortex) during action observation.  On this basis, mirror neurons were hypothesized to suppose action understanding.  The cells were later also discovered in monkey parietal cortex and M1.


Theory: Mirror neurons support action understanding, whereas most (nonmirror) neurons in macaque F5 support a motor vocabulary.  The definition of "action understanding" seems to be evolving, "at its core is the idea that self-generated action shave an inherent semantics and that observing the same action in others affords access to this action semantics."  Mirror neurons are inferred to exist in humans, but evidence is problematic, not according with observations of the original macaque study.  Analogies have been drawn to motor theory of speech perception, but this theory is not currently supported in the field of speech perception.  Mirror neurons have been used to explain human imitation, but macaques cannot imitate.  

Focuses on the claim that mirror neurons go beyond other sensory-motor cells in F5 and support action understanding, finding 8 problems:

== There Is No Evidence in Monkeys That Mirror Neurons Support Action Understanding ==

Lesions to F5 have been shown to disrupt grasping behaviour, but not action understanding.  Other experimental methods are problematic and with simpler alternative explanations.  

== Action understanding can be achieved via nonmirror neuron mechanisms ==

Rizzolatti et al papers explicitly do not exclude the possibility that other areas are involved in action understanding.  Hickok proposes one alternative, STS representing actions, and PF coordinating their interaction with the motor system in P5.

== M1 contains mirror neurons ==

The lack of mirror neurons in M1 was taken as evidence against covert generation of movement responses during action perception.  Now mirror neurons have been found in M1 it is possible that "mirror" responses are simply the facilitation of the motor system via learned association.

== The relation between macaque mirror neurons and the mirror system in humans is either nonparallel or undetermined ==

Macaques do not show behaviours that have been attributed to mirror neurons in humans, and the existence of mirror neurons in humans has not been conclusively proven.  The assumption that humans have evolved in such a way as to preserve action understanding properties of mirror neurons, but with the adaptation of also supporting imitation (as human data appears to show) is a bold one, and other possibilities are not considered.

== Action understanding in humans dissociates from neurophysiological indices of the human mirror system ==

== Action understanding and action production dissociate ==

== Damage to the inferior frontal gryus is not correlated with action understanding deficits ==

== Generalization of hte mirror system to speech recognition fails on empirical grounds == 

"... lesion studies unequivocally demonstrate that the motor theory/mirron neuron theory of speech perception is incorrect in any strong form."  A weaker form - that sensory-motor circuits do contribute to speech recognition, but in a modulatory, top-down fashion rather than being primary.

Cites alternative roles for mirror neurons as simple sensory-motor pairings, and as a mechanism for augmenting abstract concepts with sensory-motor data.},
