    abstract = {{The discovery of mirror neurons, a class of neurons that respond when a monkey performs an action and also when the monkey observes others producing the same action, has promoted a renaissance for the Motor Theory (MT) of speech perception. This is because mirror neurons seem to accomplish the same kind of one to one mapping between perception and action that MT theorizes to be the basis of human speech communication. However, this seeming correspondence is superficial, and there are theoretical and empirical reasons to temper enthusiasm about the explanatory role mirror neurons might have for speech perception. In fact, rather than providing support for MT, mirror neurons are actually inconsistent with the central tenets of MT.}},
    author = {Lotto, Andrew J. and Hickok, Gregory S. and Holt, Lori L.},
    citeulike-article-id = {4065330},
    citeulike-linkout-0 = {http://www.cell.com/cognitive-sciences/abstract/S1364-6613(09)00020-5},
    citeulike-linkout-1 = {http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.tics.2008.11.008},
    comment = {Points out that mirror system and motor theory of speech production are contradictory, in that MT characterises a module specialised for speech and nothing else, whereas mirror system is general.  Speech is only special in the former.

Broca's aphasics leave subjects with severe motor speech deficits yet speech recognition is left intact.  Indeed the entire left hemisphere 'mirror system' can be affected with speech recognition intact.  Neither MT or mirror neurons explain this.  Mixed transcortical aphasia is characterized by a severe deficit in speech comprehension despite a well-preserved ability to repeat heard speech.

Paper does not challenge that there is a production-perception link, but takes the opposite view to MT -- that production is aided by perception rather than vice-versa.  Example of bite-block in mouth in support of this view -- motor articulations change in order to preserve the same sound (perception).

Finishes by recounting the many open questions about speech perception and pointing out that a mirror system isn't a solution to them.
},
