    comment = {Despite the directionality given in the title, this review talks about 'meshing' of action and perception, which I suppose is two-way.

Says speech perception field is critical of motor theory of speech perception, but comes out in favour of many of its claims.  More favourable than Lotto et al, who later point out that this review does not mention Broca's aphasia.

Cites original motivation for motor theory from device for the blind which sonified letters with arbitrary sounds, but was unexpectedly unsuccessful.  Led to discovery of coarticulation.

Three strong claims of MT:

Speech processing is special - Interpretable in several different ways, no good supporting evidence for any of them.

Perceiving speech is perceiving gestures - Supported by several kinds of evidence: 1/ identical stimuli are perceived differently depending on the context of coarticulation. 2/ Cross-modal effects, ie McGurk effect.  3/ Speech imitation is very fast, indicating choice isn't involved.  4/ Listeners situate the acoustic signal in a space that captures its gestural causes.  Alternative accounts, such as spectral contrast and prototype context effects, don't cover all of these points.

The motor system is recruited for perceiving speech - The 'core claim' of the theory.  Not much research into behavioural evidence for a perception-production link, although what exists does support it.  The claim is backed by research into evolution - production and and perception systems must co-evolve, because motor systems provide parity for perception systems.  Reviews research into motor competence (in general, not specifically in speech) giving reason to believe that perception is attuned to general anatomical and dynamical constraints on biological movements, as well as to the specific subtleties of individual movements.  Reviews evidence of a mirror system.  Evidence specifically about speech includes overlap shown by fMRI, activation of tongue muscles when hearing lingual consonants and of lip muscles when lip reading.  Also reviews research into canonical neurons, which activate both when grasping an object and seeing an object that can be grasped in that manner, giving reason to believe that this theory of action execution and recognition may be extended to the domain of general perception of objects.

"The main lesson learned by Liberman and colleagues in 50 years of empirical research is, in the end, rather simple: Cognition, like all products of evolution, cannot be understood in isolation (e.g., Clark, 1997). Rather, understanding cognition requires comprehending that it is both embedded in a meaningful ecological context and embodied in living perceptionâ€“action systems".

