@article{Tversky77,
    abstract = {{Questions the metric and dimensional assumptions that underlie the geometric representation of similarity on both theoretical and empirical grounds. A new set-theoretical approach to similarity is developed in which objects are represented as collections of features and similarity is described as a feature-matching process. Specifically, a set of qualitative assumptions is shown to imply the contrast model, which expresses the similarity between objects as a linear combination of the measures of their common and distinctive features. Several predictions of the contrast model are tested in studies of similarity with both semantic and perceptual stimuli. The model is used to uncover, analyze, and explain a variety of empirical phenomena such as the role of common and distinctive features, the relations between judgments of similarity and difference, the presence of asymmetric similarities, and the effects of context on judgments of similarity. The contrast model generalizes standard representations of similarity data in terms of clusters and trees. It is also used to analyze the relations of prototypicality and family resemblance.}},
    author = {Tversky, A.},
    citeulike-article-id = {2919555},
    citeulike-linkout-0 = {http://psycnet.apa.org/index.cfm?fa=search.displayRecord\&\#38;uid=1978-09287-001},
    comment = {
Features of similarity

Many authors argue that dimensional representations are appropriate
for certain domains (e.g. colours, tones) but not others.  It seems
more appropriate to represent faces, countries or personalities, in
terms of many qualitative features that a few quantitative dimensions.
Similarity for such stimuli is therefore comparison of features rather
than metric distance.

(thought - gardenfors considers dimensions both qualititative and
quantitative).

Evaluates geometric approach to similarity in terms of minimality,
symmetry and triangle inequality axioms.  These axioms are often
violated by similarity measures.

Minimality: similarity with identity being equal for all stimuli does
not always hold.  For example in some experiments the probability of
judging two identical stimuli as "same" rather than "different" is not
constant for all stimuli, and an object may be identified as another
more often than itself.

[Noise and a prototype effects?]

Symmetry: similarity statements are often directional, e.g. a portrait
is more like a person, an ellipse is more like a circle, and north
korea is more like red china than the other way around.  Asymmetry is
noticeable in metaphor: turks fight like tigers, but tigers don't
fight like turks.

[A prototype effect?]

Triangle inequality: unlike minimality and symmetry, cannot be
formulated in ordinal terms, so can't be refuted with ordinal data.
However it implies that if a and b, and b and c are quite similar, a
and c can't be very different.  However Jamaica is similar to Cuba
(geographically), and cuba is similar to russia (politically) but
Jamaica is not at all like Russia.

[A domain effect]

In summary: minimality is problematic, symmetry is false and triangle
inequality is not compelling.

Proposes the "contrast model" as an alternative approach neither
dimensional or metric, but based on features which are usually binary
(e.g voiced vs voiceless consonants) or nominal (e.g. eye colour).

Similarity increases with addition of common features / deletion of
distinctive features.  

Results in an interval similarity scale preserving observed similarity
order, and expressed as a linear combination or contrast of the
measures of the common and distinctive features.

Does not define a single similarity scale, but a family of scales
differing according to the consideration given to common and distinct
features, and to directionality.  Thus tree based similarity scales
are possible as well as more geometrical ones.  

Examines similarity of figures, letters and signals on this basis.

Similarity, prototypicality and family resemblance are formally
accounted for in the model.

"There is a close tie between the assessment of similarity and the
interpretation of metaphors.  In judgments of similarity one assumes a
particular feature space, or a frame of reference, and assesses the
quality of the match between the subject and the referent.  In the
interpretation of similies, one assumes a resemblance between the
subject and the referent and searches for an interpretation of the
space that would maximizt the quality of the match.  The same pair of
objects, therefore, can be viewed as similar or different depending on
the choice of a frame of reference."

[Maybe Gardenfors' theory can be expressed in terms of Tversky's.
Although Tversky seems against geometry here, I think a geometrical
theory is a valid configuration of his contrast model.]

},
