    citeulike-article-id = {3759682},
    comment = {Critical review of timbre research

Sees lack of "widely-accepted operational or constitutive definition of timbre" as the most lasting obstacle to a better understanding of timbre.

Notes according to "just noticable differences" (JND) the average person can detence 15000 distinct pitches and 325 levels of loudness, but the answer for timbre is unknown due to its multidimensionality.

== Methods for measuring musical timbre ==

Identification - identifying instruments

Categorisation - grouping of comparison stimuli with the members of a set of standard stimuli.  Similar to identification but without requiring verbalisation

Matching - Subjective pairing of a single comparison stimulus to a single model

Verbal attributes - forced projection of an adjectival (or adverbial) schema onto a specified set of sounds, e.g. scaling stimuli on a  "brighter" or "duller" scale.

Proximity rating - e.g. MDS studies.  Similarity scaling and triadic comparisons suitable for 8 < n < 25 stimuli.   Sorting has not been used much in timbre studies but is useful for stimulus sets of 50 or even 100 elements.  

Discrimination - e.g. Grey's AAAB procedure with task to find different tone in set of four

== Discussion ==

Only discrimination tasks can uncover minute differences in timbre between stimuli, which are the norm in psychophysical studies.  Difficult to obtain clean stimuli in recordings of natural tones, so contrived synthetic tone studies are difficult to repeat under more 'natural' circumstances.

== Equalisation of pitch, loudness and duration ==

Clear that there are individual differences in perception of pitch, loudness and duration so attempts at equalisation are necessarily approximate.
Unknown to what extent pitch, loudness and duration are confounders in timbre studies.  For pitch, in some studies (Miller and Carterett, 1975), fundamental frequency has been shown to have high saliency making timbre difficult to map, and in others (Robinson and Patterson (1995)) where stimuli is very short (a few cycles) instrument type is easier to identify than pitch chroma or octave.  

The confounding effects of loudness have not been formally studied, but as perceptual loudness clearly varies per listener, and timbral similarity judgments between listeners is high, it is not felt to be a major confounder.  

Confounding effects of duration (perceived length) has not been formally studied either.  It is felt that slight deviations are not confounders, but salience increases with staccato and impulse tones.

== Perceptual and physical correlates ==

Two explanations for subjective identification of timbre, 'source' and 'interpretative'.  Source -- we perceive "underlying dynamics of physical processes" (balzano, 1986) analogous to motor theory of speech perception.  McAdams uses term from ecological psychology - "structural invariants" since they are based upon the physical structure of the vibrating system and its excitation.  Interpretative is the traditional view, that timbre is due to the input from realtime frequency analysis conducted along the basilar membrane of the inner ear.  

"We feel that the source and interpretative modes of perception contribute uniquely to identifications and timbral relationships.  Indeed, both phyisical modelling and signal analysis are effective bases for the synthesis of natural instruments.  But the relationship of the constituents of physical models to perceptual attributes has not been widely pursued."  OTOH there's a great deal of research into the envelope and time-varying spectrum relative to timbre.

So they think both contribute to timbre, but only interpretative models have really been investigated.

Studies so far find disagreement when not based upon the same set of stimuli.  The only common factor found is the spectral centroid (brightness).

},
