@article{Caclin05,
    author = {Caclin, Anne and McAdams, Stephen and Smith, Bennett K. and Winsberg, Suzanne},
    citeulike-article-id = {3746161},
    citeulike-linkout-0 = {http://scitation.aip.org/getabs/servlet/GetabsServlet?prog=normal\&id=JASMAN000118000001000471000001\&idtype=cvips\&gifs=yes},
    citeulike-linkout-1 = {http://link.aip.org/link/?JAS/118/471},
    comment = {MDS study of timbre space dimensions using synthetic tones.

Uses ANSI (1973) definition of timbre as "the perceptual attribute that distinguishes to tones of equal pitch, loudness and duration).  

Mentions reviews of timbre space studies - those based on ratings on verbal scales (kendall and carterette 1993), and on MDS (mcadams 1993, hajda et al 1997).

Compares the CLASCAL and INDSCAL models of MDS.  They both produce solutions with axes oriented in a psychologically meaningful way.  In CLASCAL the salience of each dimension is different for each latent class of subjects, and in INDSCAL different for each subject.  In the latent class approach, each subject is assumed to belong to one and only one of a small number of latent classes, and all subjects in the same class are assumed to weight all dimensions identically.  It is not known in advance to which altent class a particular subject belongs.

CONSCAL is more recent (windsberg and de soete 1997), useful where a small number of known physical parameters may be used to describe the stimuli, and it is likely that these are the very attributes upon which the subjects make their dissimilarity ratings.  The resulting MDS is constrained by the given dimensions.

MDS studies generally either use orchestral sounds or synthetic sounds constructed to imitate them.  Most studies hav eemphasized the role of spectral center of gravity (SCG, amplitude-weighted mean frequency of the energy spectrum) and attack time.  Other less systematically reported parameters include spectral flux (a mesaure of the fluctuation of the spectrum over time), spectral spread, spectral irregularity and harmonic onset asynchrony.  Along with these shared dimensions, a number of instruments are characterized by rather high specificity values, which have often been difficult to interpret.

This paper deals with two questions: (1) is a continuous space a good model of the perceptual relationships among timbres (2) if such a model is appropriate, are the proposed underlying acoustical dimensions correct?

This confirmatory study took parameters from previous MDS studies of timbre.  There were 16 different values along each acoustical dimension 'to avoid creating unwanted categories'.  The first experiment tested a space with dimensions of attack time, spectral centroid and spectral flux.  Experiment 2 investigated contextual effects on the salience of spectral flux.  Finally a space with attack time, spectral centroid and spectral irregularity was tested.

CLASCAL analyses was applied to select freely the most salient acoustical parameters.  CONSCAL was applied to allow for more refined interpretation, with an estimation of the shape of psychophysical functions for the different axes.  CONSCAL had been used only once before in the context of timbre (mcadams and winsberg 2000).

Experiment 1 - CLASCAL identified a 2D space correlated with SCG and attack time, but not with spectral flux.  The subjects were classified into two classes, both containing musically trained subjects.  CONSCAL selected a model with one class of subjects and orthogonal dimensions.  

The data confirm the perceptual significance of attack time and SCG, and that listeners use a continuous range of attack times in their ratings.  CLASCAL finds listeners do not use spectral flux, whereas CONSCAL finds they do but only with sounds with the highest spectral flux values, and with a much smaller weighting than SCG and attack time.  These results are consistent with the subjects' subjective reports.

A resulting hypothesis was that spectral flux salience might be sensitive to contextual effects, particularly to the number of other dimensions varying concurrently.

Experiment 2

Isolated contextual effects by choosing three sets of stimuli: A - SCG kept constant, B - attack time kept constant and C - both SCG and attack time kept constant.

Confirmed the significance of attack time and SCG.  Spectral flux information was used to a larger extent when variation only ocurred along one concurrent dimension instead of two, and was more strongly inhibited by attack time than by SCG.  Hypothesis confirmed.

Experiment 3

Looked for third dimension of timbre salient enough to be used in dissimilarity ratings when both attack time and SCG vary.  Spectral flux dimension was replaced by a selective attenuation of even harmonics relative to odd harmonics.

Again, SCG and attack time confirmed as salient.  Spectral irregularity was also confirmed as a salient parameter.  All three appear to have the same perceptual status along a continuous scale.

== General discussion ==

Confirmed attack time, spectral centroid, spectral flux and attenuation of even harmonics explained timbre space dimensions, although spectral flux was hardly used when attack time and SCG varied concurrently.

Logarithm of attack time (not linear attack time) used in ratings.

Spectral centroid seems to be ordered on a linear frequency scale.

Attennuation in dB of even harmonics was used linearly in ratings.

Both CONSCAL and CLASCAL appear adequate to model dissimilarity ratings.

Inter-individual differences exist, whether these differences reflect different in decision or perception is an open question.

},
