@book{Borg05,
    abstract = {{The book provides a comprehensive treatment of multidimensional scaling (MDS),
a family of statistical techniques for analyzing the structure of
(dis)similarity data. Such data are widespread, including, for example,
intercorrelations of survey items, direct ratings on the similarity on choice
objects, or trade indices for a set of countries. MDS represents the data as
distances among points in a geometric space of low dimensionality. This map
can help to see patterns in the data that are not obvious from the data
matrices. MDS is also used as a psychological model for judgments of
similarity and preference.

This book may be used as an introduction to MDS for students in psychology,
sociology, and marketing. The prerequisite is an elementary background in
statistics. The book is also well suited for a variety of advanced courses on
MDS topics. All the mathematics required for more advanced topics is developed
systematically.

This second edition is not only a complete overhaul of its predecessor, but
also adds some 140 pages of new material. Many chapters are revised or have
sections reflecting new insights and developments in MDS. There are two new
chapters, one on asymmetric models and the other on unfolding. There are also
numerous exercises that help the reader to practice what he or she has
learned, and to delve deeper into the models and its intricacies. These
exercises make it easier to use this edition in a course. All data sets used
in the book can be downloaded from the web. The appendix on computer programs
has also been updated and enlarged to reflect the state of the art.}},
    author = {Borg, I. and Groenen, P. J. F.},
    citeulike-article-id = {2910442},
    citeulike-linkout-0 = {http://www.amazon.ca/exec/obidos/redirect?tag=citeulike09-20\&amp;path=ASIN/0387251502},
    citeulike-linkout-1 = {http://www.amazon.de/exec/obidos/redirect?tag=citeulike01-21\&amp;path=ASIN/0387251502},
    citeulike-linkout-2 = {http://www.amazon.fr/exec/obidos/redirect?tag=citeulike06-21\&amp;path=ASIN/0387251502},
    citeulike-linkout-3 = {http://www.amazon.jp/exec/obidos/ASIN/0387251502},
    citeulike-linkout-4 = {http://www.amazon.co.uk/exec/obidos/ASIN/0387251502/citeulike00-21},
    citeulike-linkout-5 = {http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/redirect?tag=citeulike07-20\&path=ASIN/0387251502},
    citeulike-linkout-6 = {http://www.worldcat.org/isbn/0387251502},
    citeulike-linkout-7 = {http://books.google.com/books?vid=ISBN0387251502},
    citeulike-linkout-8 = {http://www.amazon.com/gp/search?keywords=0387251502\&index=books\&linkCode=qs},
    citeulike-linkout-9 = {http://www.librarything.com/isbn/0387251502},
    comment = {Modern multi-dimensional scaling

Four purposes

a) method that represents (dis)similarity data as distances in a low
dimensional space in order to make these data accessible to visual
inspection and exploration

Allows researcher to *see* structure in the data


b) technique that allows one to test if and how certain criteria by
which one can distinguish among different objects of interest are
mirrored in corresponding empirical differences of these objects

... what one wants to know is if and how the facets (dimensions,
factors, features, etc.) by which the items are conceptually
distinguished are reflected in corresponding differences among
observations on these items.

c) data-analytic approach that allows one to discover the dimensions
that underlie judgments of (dis)similarity

d) psychological model that explains judgments of dissimilarity in
terms of a rule that mimics a particular type of distance function.

... involves a particular distance function that is defined on
particular dimensions and is interpreted quite literally as a
psychological composition rule.


Metrical vs Ordinal MDS

Usually result in similar maps.  Ordinal MDS useful where test
subjects rank data ordinally rather than differentiating metrically.


Measures of fit

Badness of fit measure known as loss function

raw Stress = sum-of-squares of errors between pairs.

Stress = normed raw Stress (avoids scale dependency, so disimilarities
meters do not have greater stress than those in kilometres).

Stress similar to a correlation coefficient, except that it measures
the badness-of-fit rather than the goodness-of-fit.

General term for similarity and dissimilarity is proximity.

Shepard diagram of Stress - proximities vs MDS distances.  Givesnumber
of points to be fitted, optimal regression line, size of deviations,
possible outliers and systematic deviations from the requested
deviation line.  Particularly informative for ordinal MDS.

Stress (or fit) per point table allows identification of best and
worse points.

Norms for Stress (in context of ordinal MDS): 
Guttman (in Porrat, 1974) proposes coefficient of alienation K should
be less that 0.15 for an acceptably precise MDS solution "under usual
circumstances".

Scree plot - Stress vs dimensionality.  'Elbow' in the curve
corresponds to the dimensionality that should be chosen.

For Stress-1 coefficient using ordinal MDS, Kruskal (1964a) suggests
benchmarks: 0.2 = poor, 0.1 = fair, 0.05 = good, 0.025 = excellent, 0
= perfect.  However these benchmarks lead to misuse - an MDS solution
may have high Stress simply as a consequence of high error in the
data, and finding a precise representation for the data does not imply
anything about its scientific value.


Dependencies of Stress:

- n, number of points - high n = higher stress
- m, dimensionality of MDS space: higher m = lower Stress
- more error in data means higher Stre
- more ties in the data allow for loewr Stress in general (for ordinal
  MDS with weak monotonicity)
- more missing data lead to lower Stress in general
- interval MDS generally leads to higher Stress than ordinal

Stress is a "technical measure" and should be tempered by
corresponding dimensions with prior knowledge or theory about the
scaled objects.


Collecting proximities

Anchor stimulus method, yielding conditional data - Hamish's chosen
one.  Task is easier and yields more reliable data.  However they
require more judgments overall and are 'less comparable'.  Bijmolt and
Wedel found that free collecting condition data was considered boring
and fatiguing by the respondants.  Pairwise copmarisons ranked best
for quality of data and MDS solution, followed by free sorting.

Balancing

Position effect can be reduced by randomly picking order, and timing
effects by picking a random order for the object pairs.  An
alternative is to balance position and timing effects by explicit
planning.  Ross (1934) developed a method for that purpose, superior
to random method if the number of objects is small.  A computer
program for Ross ordering was written by Cohen and Davison (1973).


Planned Incomplete Data Designs

Even if we randomly remove 80\% of the data, excellent recovery of MDS
space is still possible (Spence and Domoney, 1974).  Graef and Spence
(1979) showed configurations are poorly recovered if the proximities
for the largest distances are missing.  These studies are based on
simulations with many points, reasonable error in data, known
dimensionality etc, which are often difficult to assess in practice.


Thoughts

Asking subjects for metrical datass but treating it as ordinal seems
wrong headed.  Difficult to make metrical judgements -- a memory task
(cf christophe).

Could known universal timbre dimensions such as brightness/spectral
centroid be held constant when varying source parameters?

},
