@mastersthesis{Cho05,
    abstract = {{Modern linguistic theory suggests that the sign is arbitrary, that the relationship
between signifier and signified has no discernible pattern. ( â€ Dogâ€ could mean cat,
and vice versa.) Marketing experts and advertisers, those who create names for new
products, think otherwise, that the sounds of words and neologisms can evoke images
which elicit an emotional impact. Different sounds can  â€ feelâ€ sharp or dull, for example;
they can give a phenomenological response. Poets, of course, realize that the sounds
words make can be used towards expressive means. While morphemesâ€”roots,
prefixes and suffixesâ€”have generally been considered the base level of meaning,
some studies suggest that phonemes can influence meaning on a subconscious level,
perhaps resulting from the physiology of how we produce different sounds in speech.
       In this paper and accompanying project, I am interested in the relationship
between spoken and written language and will look at examples in which meaning
plays a integral role in how speech and writing are represented. I will be looking at
cases in which the signifier and signified connect in ways Saussure would not have
expected. I am especially interested in what might be considered a synaesthetic
result: sound and vision are tightly coupled, tied together through meaning. This paper
will explore the relationships among issues of sound, writing, meaning, the machine,
the line, and the body, by considering previous explorations including invented
alphabets, phonetic writing systems, machines for automatic transcription of speech,
among others.}},
    author = {Cho, Peter},
    citeulike-article-id = {3380252},
    comment = {Disagrees with Saussure's principle that "the bond between the signifier and the signified is arbitrary".

Compares style and mood of handwriting with paralinguistic prosody in speech.

Phonosemantics/sound symbolism - connections between sound and meaning.

3 types of sound symbolism:
  corporeal - shout, groan, laugh, clearing of throat
  imitative - knock, swicsh, snap, sing-dong
  synesthetic - acoustic symbolism of non-acoustic phenomena, ie prolonging (hu-u-ge), altering intonation, making vowel sounds deeper/shallower (ie teeny, itsy-bitsy, skinny, humungous, large, grand, vast)

clustering - glisten, glitter, glimmer, glass, glow

applications in marketing and sound poetry...

Suggests these phono-semantics are culturally specific.

Ideal alphabets
types:
  ideographic - one sign per word
  logographic - a glyph/character represents a concept
  syllabic - each sign represents a combination of consonants and a vowel
  phonetic - each sign roughly represents a phoneme of a spoken language

Roman alphabet used to write a large variety of historically unrelated languages.  Ancient greek has nearly one-to-one relation between phoneme and letter.  Adoption and adaption has led to many irregularities and complexities, for example in english.

hangul - invented in 1443, in wide use today, the official alphabet of North and South Korea.  Hangul consonants are based on the profile of the tongue.

Several attempts of rationalisation of the western alphabet have been less successful...

Takeluma is a nice phonetic alphabet introduced in the thesis.  Choice of consonants was informed by intuition and by "Gods of the Word: Archetypes in the Consonants" by Margaret Magnus.  The 14 vowel sounds were represented by a split line, the resulting shape defining where the sound is produced and how wide the mouth is.
},
    keywords = {alphabets, speech, vocables},
    posted-at = {2008-10-06 16:17:39},
    priority = {0},
    school = {University of California, Los Angeles},
    title = {{Takeluma: An Exploration of Sound, Meaning, and Writing}},
    year = {2005}
}

